== '''Roberino''' ==


(Rah-bur-een-o)

''noun''

1. A popular cocktail drink with an illustrious and mischievous past.
2. The drink has recently been making a frothy comeback due to the tireless efforts of NYC resident
Robert "The Colonel" Schmalz*.

*See also: KFC (or the popular alternative "KFC and Tequila", dinner-theater jousting, backyard
wrestling accidents, Chuck Norris, and the nickname "short dagger".

'''History'''

The history of the Roberino is a tale of love, wickedness, inspiration, and occasional public drunkenness.
During the steamy summer of 1781 Captain Yukon Cornelius was hot on the trail of a treasure
containing rare gold coins left on a recently shipwrecked Spanish Galleon. Soon after finding the
treasure, Yukon was blow-darted to death by local native warriors. His dying wish was almost prophetic
as it refers to technology that wouldn’t be developed for 200 years: "Order the air strike and send these
papaya-eaters back to the stone age!!!........and by the way.....save the Roberino drink!!!".
The gold coins were taken and lost forever, but the historical parchment containing the original recipe
for the Roberino drink was recovered by a surviving shipmate and buried for safe keeping.
Fast forward to 1986: Robert Schmalz was in the Honduras leading his glee club on a sea shell gathering
expedition for the charity "Save the Whales but Kill the Seals". While attempting to relieve himself in a
patch of bushes he stumbled upon a half-buried box that contained the Roberino recipe. Feeling that this
discovery was no accident, he made it his mission in life to bring the Roberino back to the lips of the
cocktail connoisseurs everywhere.
Rob says, "From the outhouse to the White House, the Roberino is sure to quelch the saltiest of thirsts.
Hell yeah baby!!!"

'''Recent Drink Reviews:'''

NYC Mayor Michael Blomberg: "I love the Roberino. It is really great. Okay now give me my thousand
bucks for saying that."

Former Minnesota Governor Jesse Vntura: "You can shove this drink up your kiester. I've had better
drinks containing motor oil. By the way -- get off my property before I knock you into next week!"

Boutique investment banker Michael Sellman (after being served a Roberino at a society breakfast): "A Roberino, Oh My! This day will be just glorious!!!"